{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658165"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:42:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:42:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20712"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0,0,0,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13588"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78145"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"12524"},{"type":"tags","id":"12591"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is admitted to hospital following a motor vehicle accident. He has sustained bilateral femoral fractures and undergoes surgical fixation. Two days after the injury, he develops sudden onset of tachypnoea, dyspnoea, confusion, and restlessness. Physical examination reveals a petechial rash on his chest and upper arms. Laboratory tests show a haemoglobin of 95 g/L (130-170) and platelet count of 90 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fat embolism syndrome","Traumatic brain injury","Acute respiratory distress syndrome","Pulmonary thromboembolism","Disseminated intravascular coagulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFat embolism syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this case. It typically presents 1-3 days after long bone fractures with a characteristic triad of respiratory distress (tachypnoea, dyspnoea), neurological symptoms (confusion, restlessness, delirium), and petechial rash. Laboratory findings often include anaemia and thrombocytopenia. In this case the timing of symptom onset (two days post-injury) and the presence of bilateral femoral fractures are highly consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary thromboembolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset dyspnoea and chest pain but would not explain the neurological symptoms, petechial rash, or haematological abnormalities seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E can occur after trauma but usually presents with more severe coagulopathy and bleeding from multiple sites, not just a petechial rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute respiratory distress syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can develop after trauma but would not typically cause the neurological symptoms or petechial rash described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraumatic brain injury\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the neurological symptoms but would not account for the respiratory distress, petechial rash, or haematological abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFat embolism syndrome occurs in a minority of patients with fat embolism (which is present in about 90% of severe skeletal injuries). The syndrome has a mortality rate of 5-15% and is characterised by fat globules entering the circulation after bone marrow disruption, leading to pulmonary, neurological, and haematological manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fat embolism syndrome typically presents 1-3 days after long bone fractures with respiratory distress, neurological symptoms, anaemia, and thrombocytopenia.","Fat embolism occurs in approximately 90% of severe skeletal injuries, but only a minority develop symptomatic fat embolism syndrome.","The mortality rate of fat embolism syndrome is 5-15% of cases.","A petechial rash, seen in 20-50% of cases, is a useful diagnostic clue for fat embolism syndrome."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 131."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78145"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78145"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T13:36:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T13:36:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13588"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","